@sergey-tihon initially I thought you were talking about the lifetime of the AzureCP access token, but now I understand you meant the lifetime of the SAML token that users receive from Azure AD upon successful authentication.

@w3-dev AzureCP is not impacted about the 1h lifetime of its access token: When it expires, it just gets a new one and it's completely transparent.

@YayForJam setting AccessTokenLifetime to 24h hours was needed only for the SharePoint enterprise application, it is irrelevant for AzureCP application (see my comment above).

To summarize: the lifetime of the SAML token given by Azure AD to users upon successful authentication is the main (almost only) setting that defines the user session lifetime, and you cannot increase it in SharePoint no matter what configuration you change (you can only lower it). 
AzureCP has no action/impact on the user session lifetime, it uses its own access token that has its own lifetime.

